-- 05-meta-cell-designer-frames.cell (v0.2)
-- Execution trace of 05-meta-cell-designer.cell via eval-one
--
-- v0.2 execution notes:
--   - File-scope ⊨? active: retry max 3 with failure context, then ⊥
--   - critique has guard clause: only enters ready set if len(awkward-spots) > 0
--   - redesign uses given? for critique outputs (tolerates ⊥ from guard skip)
--   - design-cells oracles are aspirational under ⊢∘ management
--   - ⊢∘ until condition: len(critique→problems) = 0 or critique→problems = ⊥
--
-- Domain: "An automated code review system that checks for security
-- vulnerabilities, suggests fixes, and verifies the fixes don't break
-- existing tests."

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- READY-SET ANALYSIS (initial graph)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Cells in the program:
--   domain              — given: description ≡ (literal)         → READY
--   cell-spec           — given: spec-path ≡ (literal)           → READY
--   decompose           — given: domain→description              → BLOCKED (needs domain)
--   design-cells        — given: decompose→*, cell-spec→*        → BLOCKED (needs decompose, cell-spec)
--   trace-readiness     — given: §program                        → BLOCKED (needs design-cells)
--   simulate-oracles    — given: §program, trace→ready-order     → BLOCKED (needs design-cells, trace)
--   critique            — given: §program, oracles→awkward-spots → BLOCKED (needs design-cells, oracles)
--                          GUARD: len(awkward-spots) > 0
--   redesign            — given: §program, critique→* (given?)   → BLOCKED (needs design-cells, critique)
--   emit-program        — given: redesign→§program', domain→desc → BLOCKED (needs redesign, domain)
--
-- ⊢∘ evolve manages: design-cells through critique, redesign
-- Convergence: len(critique→problems) = 0 or critique→problems = ⊥
--
-- Ready set: { domain, cell-spec } — both have literal bindings
-- Pick: domain (arbitrary — confluence guarantees order doesn't matter)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 0: evaluate domain (trivial pass-through)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { domain, cell-spec }
-- Pick: domain

⊢ domain
  given description ≡ "An automated code review system that checks for security vulnerabilities, suggests fixes, and verifies the fixes don't break existing tests."
  yield description

-- eval-one: domain is a pass-through. description is already bound via given ≡.
-- No ∴ body, no ⊢= body. Yield inherits from given.

  yield description ≡ "An automated code review system that checks for security vulnerabilities, suggests fixes, and verifies the fixes don't break existing tests."

-- oracle check:
--   ⊨ description is a clear problem domain → ✓
--     (describes inputs: code; processing: check/suggest/verify; outputs: security reports)

-- state after frame 0: domain frozen.
-- Ready set: { cell-spec }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 1: evaluate cell-spec (⊢= hard cell, deterministic)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { cell-spec }
-- Blocked: { decompose } — needs domain→description (now available!)
--   decompose will join ready set next.

⊢ cell-spec
  given spec-path ≡ "docs/design/cell-v0.2-spec.md"
  yield symbols, execution-model, patterns

-- eval-one: all three yields are ⊢= hard bodies. Deterministic evaluation.

  yield symbols ≡ "⊢ (declare cell), ∴ (soft body), ⊢= (hard body), ⊨ (oracle), ⊨? (recovery), § (quotation), «» (interpolation), ≡ (binding), → (output access), ▸ (refinement), ⊢∘ (evolution), ⊢⊢ (spawner), ⊥ (bottom), given? (optional dep), where (guard clause)"

  yield execution-model ≡ "eval-one via Kahn's algorithm: find cells with all givens bound and guards true, evaluate one, check oracles, freeze yields. Monotonic — yields only get bound. Document IS the state. Guards skip cells cleanly (yields → ⊥). given? tolerates ⊥."

  yield patterns ≡ "proof-carrying computation (LLM finds, code verifies), self-crystallization (∴ → ⊢=), evolution loops (⊢∘ rewrites soft cells), spawners (⊢⊢ grows frontier, accumulate or replace), cell-as-agent (inbox → dispatch → act), guard-based dispatch (given x where cond)"

-- oracle: none on cell-spec. Pure ⊢= cells need no runtime oracle.

-- state after frame 1: cell-spec frozen.
-- Ready set: { decompose } — domain→description and cell-spec→* all available

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 2: evaluate decompose (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { decompose }
-- Blocked: { design-cells } — needs decompose→components, decompose→dataflow

⊢ decompose
  given domain→description ≡ "An automated code review system that checks for security vulnerabilities, suggests fixes, and verifies the fixes don't break existing tests."
  yield components[], dataflow[]

  ∴ Analyze the domain and decompose into logical components...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield components ≡ [
    "parse-diff: Parse the incoming code diff to extract changed files, hunks, and line ranges. Input: raw diff. Output: structured file list with change regions.",
    "classify-changes: Classify each changed region by risk level (high: auth/crypto/input-handling, medium: data flow, low: UI/logging). Input: parsed diff. Output: risk-classified regions.",
    "scan-vulnerabilities: For each high/medium-risk region, scan for known vulnerability patterns (SQL injection, XSS, buffer overflow, insecure deserialization, hardcoded secrets). Input: risk regions. Output: vulnerability findings with severity and location.",
    "suggest-fixes: For each vulnerability found, generate a concrete code fix. Input: vulnerability + surrounding code context. Output: patch suggestion with explanation.",
    "run-tests: Execute the existing test suite against the proposed fixes to verify nothing breaks. Input: original code + patches. Output: test results (pass/fail per test).",
    "compile-report: Aggregate all findings, fixes, and test results into a final review report. Input: vulnerabilities, fixes, test results. Output: structured review report."
  ]

  yield dataflow ≡ [
    "parse-diff→file-list, parse-diff→change-regions → classify-changes",
    "classify-changes→risk-regions → scan-vulnerabilities",
    "scan-vulnerabilities→findings → suggest-fixes",
    "suggest-fixes→patches, parse-diff→file-list → run-tests",
    "scan-vulnerabilities→findings, suggest-fixes→patches, run-tests→test-results → compile-report"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(components) ≥ 4 → ✓ (6 components)
--   ⊨ each component has a clear single responsibility → ✓
--     parse-diff: parsing only. classify-changes: risk assessment only.
--     scan-vulnerabilities: detection only. suggest-fixes: remediation only.
--     run-tests: verification only. compile-report: aggregation only.
--   ⊨ dataflow forms a DAG → ✓ (linear chain with one fan-in at compile-report)
--   ⊨ dataflow covers every component → ✓ (all 6 components appear)

-- state after frame 2: decompose frozen.
-- Ready set: { design-cells } — decompose→components and decompose→dataflow now available
--   (cell-spec→symbols and cell-spec→execution-model already frozen)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 3: evaluate design-cells (soft cell, LLM) — ⊢∘ managed, iteration 1
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { design-cells }
-- Blocked: { trace-readiness } — needs design-cells→§program
-- NOTE: design-cells is managed by ⊢∘ evolve. Its oracles are ASPIRATIONAL.

⊢ design-cells
  given decompose→components ≡ ["parse-diff: Parse the incoming code diff...", "classify-changes: Classify each changed region...", "scan-vulnerabilities: For each high/medium-risk region...", "suggest-fixes: For each vulnerability found...", "run-tests: Execute the existing test suite...", "compile-report: Aggregate all findings..."]
  given decompose→dataflow ≡ ["parse-diff→... → classify-changes", "classify-changes→... → scan-vulnerabilities", "scan-vulnerabilities→... → suggest-fixes", "suggest-fixes→..., parse-diff→... → run-tests", "...→ compile-report"]
  given cell-spec→symbols ≡ "⊢, ∴, ⊢=, ⊨, ⊨?, §, «», ≡, →, ▸, ⊢∘, ⊢⊢, ⊥, given?, where"
  given cell-spec→execution-model ≡ "eval-one via Kahn's..."
  yield §program

  ∴ Translate the components and dataflow into a valid Cell program...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield §program ≡ §«
    ⊢ diff-input
      given raw-diff
      yield raw-diff
      ⊨ raw-diff is a valid unified diff format

    ⊢ parse-diff ▸ crystallized
      given diff-input→raw-diff
      yield file-list[], change-regions[]
      ⊢= parse unified diff into structured file list and change regions
      ⊨ length(file-list) ≥ 1
      ⊨ each change-region maps to a file in file-list

    ⊢ classify-changes
      given parse-diff→change-regions
      yield risk-regions[]
      ∴ Classify each change region in «parse-diff→change-regions» by risk:
        high (auth, crypto, input handling), medium (data flow, API boundaries),
        low (UI, logging, comments). Tag each region with its risk level.
      ⊨ each region has a risk level ∈ { "high", "medium", "low" }
      ⊨ risk-regions covers all change-regions

    ⊢⊢ spawn-scanners
      given classify-changes→risk-regions where any(risk-regions, r -> r→risk != "low")
      given §vuln-scan-template
      yield §scan-cells[]
      until length(scan-cells) = count(classify-changes→risk-regions, r -> r→risk != "low")
      max 20
      accumulate
      ∴ For each high or medium risk region, spawn a vulnerability scanner cell.
        Low-risk regions are skipped (no security scan needed).
      ⊨ each scan-cell targets exactly one risk region

    ⊢ vuln-scan-template
      given region
      given risk-level
      yield findings[], severity
      ∴ Scan «region» for vulnerability patterns appropriate to its «risk-level»:
        - high: SQL injection, XSS, CSRF, buffer overflow, insecure deserialization,
          hardcoded secrets, authentication bypass
        - medium: data leakage, insecure defaults, missing rate limiting,
          unvalidated redirects
        Report each finding with type, location, severity, and evidence.
      ⊨ each finding has type, location, severity, and evidence
      ⊨ severity ∈ { "critical", "high", "medium", "low", "info" }

    ⊢ collect-findings
      given vuln-scan-*→findings
      given vuln-scan-*→severity
      yield all-findings[], has-vulnerabilities
      ⊢= all-findings ← flatten(vuln-scan-*→findings)
      ⊢= has-vulnerabilities ← len(all-findings) > 0

    ⊢ suggest-fixes
      given collect-findings→all-findings where collect-findings→has-vulnerabilities = true
      given parse-diff→file-list
      yield patches[], explanations[]
      ∴ For each vulnerability in «collect-findings→all-findings», generate a
        concrete code fix. Use the file context from «parse-diff→file-list»
        to ensure the patch applies cleanly. Include an explanation of what
        the fix does and why.
      ⊨ length(patches) = length(collect-findings→all-findings)
      ⊨ each patch is syntactically valid code
      ⊨ each explanation describes the vulnerability and the fix

    ⊢ run-tests
      given suggest-fixes→patches
      given parse-diff→file-list
      yield test-results[], all-pass
      ∴ Simulate running the existing test suite after applying «suggest-fixes→patches»
        to «parse-diff→file-list». Report pass/fail for each test, noting any
        regressions introduced by the security fixes.
      ⊨ test-results covers the full test suite
      ⊢= all-pass ← all(test-results, t -> t→status = "pass")

    ⊢ compile-report
      given collect-findings→all-findings
      given suggest-fixes→patches
      given suggest-fixes→explanations
      given run-tests→test-results
      given run-tests→all-pass
      yield review-report
      ∴ Compile a final security review report:
        - Summary: number of vulnerabilities found, by severity
        - For each finding: description, location, suggested fix, test impact
        - Overall verdict: safe to merge (all-pass and all fixes applied)
          or needs attention (test regressions or unresolved vulnerabilities)
      ⊨ review-report is structured with summary, findings, and verdict
      ⊨ if all-pass = true then verdict recommends merge
      ⊨ if all-pass = false then verdict flags regressions
  »

-- oracle checks (ASPIRATIONAL — ⊢∘ managed):
--   ⊨ §program contains only valid Cell syntax → ✓ (all cells use valid v0.2 syntax)
--   ⊨ every component has a corresponding ⊢ cell → ✓
--     parse-diff ↔ parse-diff. classify-changes ↔ classify-changes.
--     scan-vulnerabilities ↔ vuln-scan-template + spawn-scanners + collect-findings.
--     suggest-fixes ↔ suggest-fixes. run-tests ↔ run-tests.
--     compile-report ↔ compile-report.
--   ⊨ every dataflow edge expressed via given/→ → ✓ (checked all connections)
--   ⊨ at least one cell uses ⊢= → ✓ (parse-diff ▸ crystallized, collect-findings ⊢=, run-tests partial ⊢=)
--   ⊨ at least one cell has ⊨ oracles → ✓ (multiple cells)
-- NOTE: aspirational oracles all pass in iteration 1. Good starting quality.

-- state after frame 3: design-cells frozen (iteration 1).
-- Ready set: { trace-readiness }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 4: evaluate trace-readiness (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { trace-readiness }
-- Blocked: { simulate-oracles } — needs trace-readiness→ready-order

⊢ trace-readiness
  given §program ≡ §«...the full program from design-cells...»
  yield ready-order[], blocking-map

  ∴ Simulate eval-one scheduling on the program...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield ready-order ≡ [
    "diff-input (given ≡ literal — ready immediately)",
    "parse-diff (needs diff-input→raw-diff)",
    "classify-changes (needs parse-diff→change-regions)",
    "spawn-scanners (needs classify-changes→risk-regions, guard: any non-low risk)",
    "vuln-scan-0..N (spawned, each needs region + risk-level — ready on spawn)",
    "collect-findings (needs vuln-scan-*→findings — wildcard, waits for all)",
    "suggest-fixes (needs collect-findings→all-findings, guard: has-vulnerabilities = true)",
    "run-tests (needs suggest-fixes→patches)",
    "compile-report (needs collect-findings, suggest-fixes, run-tests)"
  ]

  yield blocking-map ≡ {
    "parse-diff": ["diff-input→raw-diff"],
    "classify-changes": ["parse-diff→change-regions"],
    "spawn-scanners": ["classify-changes→risk-regions", "GUARD: any(risk-regions, r→risk != 'low')"],
    "vuln-scan-*": ["spawned by spawn-scanners — blocked until spawner fires"],
    "collect-findings": ["vuln-scan-*→findings (wildcard — all matches must freeze)"],
    "suggest-fixes": ["collect-findings→all-findings", "GUARD: has-vulnerabilities = true"],
    "run-tests": ["suggest-fixes→patches"],
    "compile-report": ["collect-findings→all-findings", "suggest-fixes→patches", "suggest-fixes→explanations", "run-tests→test-results", "run-tests→all-pass"]
  }

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ ready-order is a valid topological sort → ✓ (each cell listed after its deps)
--   ⊨ every cell appears exactly once → ✓ (9 cells + spawned vuln-scan-* as group)
--   ⊨ no cell permanently blocked → ✓
--     Note: suggest-fixes has a guard (has-vulnerabilities = true). If guard is false,
--     suggest-fixes yields ⊥. run-tests depends on suggest-fixes→patches — blocked by ⊥.
--     compile-report depends on run-tests — also blocked. But compile-report also
--     depends on collect-findings directly. This is a design issue: if no vulnerabilities
--     are found, the report should still emit (clean bill of health). Awkward spot.

-- state after frame 4: trace-readiness frozen.
-- Ready set: { simulate-oracles }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 5: evaluate simulate-oracles (soft cell, LLM)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { simulate-oracles }
-- Blocked: { critique } — needs simulate-oracles→awkward-spots + guard

⊢ simulate-oracles
  given §program ≡ §«...»
  given trace-readiness→ready-order ≡ [...]
  yield oracle-results[], awkward-spots[]

  ∴ Classify every ⊨ oracle in the program...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield oracle-results ≡ [
    { cell: "diff-input", oracle: "raw-diff is a valid unified diff format", type: "structural", note: "Checkable by regex for @@, +/-, file headers" },
    { cell: "parse-diff", oracle: "length(file-list) ≥ 1", type: "deterministic", note: "Pure length check" },
    { cell: "parse-diff", oracle: "each change-region maps to a file in file-list", type: "structural", note: "Cross-reference check, could be ⊢=" },
    { cell: "classify-changes", oracle: "each region has risk ∈ {high, medium, low}", type: "deterministic", note: "Enum membership check" },
    { cell: "classify-changes", oracle: "risk-regions covers all change-regions", type: "deterministic", note: "Length comparison" },
    { cell: "spawn-scanners", oracle: "each scan-cell targets one region", type: "structural", note: "1:1 mapping check" },
    { cell: "vuln-scan-template", oracle: "each finding has type/location/severity/evidence", type: "structural", note: "Schema check" },
    { cell: "vuln-scan-template", oracle: "severity ∈ {critical, high, medium, low, info}", type: "deterministic", note: "Enum check" },
    { cell: "suggest-fixes", oracle: "length(patches) = length(all-findings)", type: "deterministic", note: "1:1 correspondence" },
    { cell: "suggest-fixes", oracle: "each patch is syntactically valid code", type: "semantic", note: "Requires parsing or LLM judgment — NOT deterministic" },
    { cell: "suggest-fixes", oracle: "each explanation describes the vuln and fix", type: "semantic", note: "Requires LLM judgment" },
    { cell: "run-tests", oracle: "test-results covers the full test suite", type: "ambiguous", note: "What is 'the full test suite'? Not defined in this program. The program has no given for the test suite itself — it just says 'existing test suite'. Where does it come from?" },
    { cell: "compile-report", oracle: "if all-pass then verdict recommends merge", type: "deterministic", note: "Conditional oracle — if all-pass is false, vacuously satisfied" },
    { cell: "compile-report", oracle: "if not all-pass then verdict flags regressions", type: "deterministic", note: "Conditional oracle" },
    { cell: "compile-report", oracle: "report is structured with summary/findings/verdict", type: "semantic", note: "Schema check — could be tightened to structural" }
  ]

  yield awkward-spots ≡ [
    "AWKWARD-1: run-tests oracle 'covers the full test suite' is AMBIGUOUS. The test suite is never provided as an input. run-tests says 'simulate running the existing test suite' but there is no given for the test suite. How can we verify coverage of something undefined?",
    "AWKWARD-2: suggest-fixes has a guard (has-vulnerabilities = true) but run-tests depends on suggest-fixes→patches. If no vulnerabilities are found, suggest-fixes is SKIPPED, patches = ⊥, run-tests is blocked by ⊥, compile-report is blocked. The clean-bill-of-health path is broken — the program hangs when there are zero vulnerabilities.",
    "AWKWARD-3: vuln-scan-template oracle 'each finding has type, location, severity, and evidence' is STRUCTURAL but tested only at the template level. When spawn-scanners creates vuln-scan-0, vuln-scan-1, etc., each inherits this oracle. But the template itself is never evaluated (used as §-data only). The oracle only fires on spawned instances — which is correct, but should be noted.",
    "AWKWARD-4: compile-report's oracle 'report is structured with summary, findings, and verdict' is SEMANTIC but could be tightened to a STRUCTURAL check (e.g., report contains sections named 'Summary', 'Findings', 'Verdict'). Vagueness invites LLM judgment where determinism would suffice."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ oracle-results covers every ⊨ → ✓ (15 oracles across 7 cells, all classified)
--   ⊨ each result classifies the oracle type → ✓
--   ⊨ awkward-spots identifies genuine design weaknesses → ✓
--     AWKWARD-1: real problem (undefined input)
--     AWKWARD-2: real problem (broken ⊥ propagation path)
--     AWKWARD-3: valid observation (not a bug, but worth noting)
--     AWKWARD-4: real improvement opportunity (semantic → structural)

-- state after frame 5: simulate-oracles frozen.
-- Ready set: evaluating guard on critique...
--   critique guard: len(awkward-spots) > 0 → len(4) > 0 → true → critique enters ready set
-- Ready set: { critique }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 6: evaluate critique (soft cell, LLM) — guard passed
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { critique }
-- Guard: len(awkward-spots) > 0 → ✓ (4 awkward spots found)
-- Blocked: { redesign } — needs critique→problems (given?)

⊢ critique
  given §program ≡ §«...»
  given simulate-oracles→awkward-spots ≡ ["AWKWARD-1...", "AWKWARD-2...", "AWKWARD-3...", "AWKWARD-4..."]
    where len(awkward-spots) > 0 → ✓ (guard satisfied, 4 items)
  given trace-readiness→blocking-map ≡ {...}
  yield problems[], suggestions[]

  ∴ Review the program for design problems...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield problems ≡ [
    "P1 (from AWKWARD-2, CRITICAL): The zero-vulnerability path is broken. suggest-fixes guard (has-vulnerabilities = true) means clean code produces ⊥ for patches. run-tests depends on patches → blocked by ⊥. compile-report depends on run-tests → blocked by ⊥. The program HANGS when the code has no security issues — the most common case.",
    "P2 (from AWKWARD-1): run-tests references 'the existing test suite' but no cell provides it as input. The test suite should be a given on the root input cell (like diff-input), or run-tests should declare what tests it simulates.",
    "P3 (from AWKWARD-4): compile-report's structure oracle is too vague. 'Structured with summary, findings, and verdict' should be a structural check, not a semantic one.",
    "P4 (new, from dataflow review): compile-report depends on both suggest-fixes AND collect-findings. If suggest-fixes is skipped (no vulnerabilities), compile-report should still be reachable via collect-findings. But compile-report also requires run-tests→test-results. This compounds P1."
  ]

  yield suggestions ≡ [
    "S1 (fixes P1+P4): Use given? on compile-report for suggest-fixes and run-tests outputs. If no vulnerabilities: suggest-fixes is skipped (⊥), run-tests is blocked (⊥), compile-report receives ⊥ for those fields via given? and generates a 'no vulnerabilities found' report. Also add given? on run-tests for suggest-fixes→patches so run-tests can skip cleanly when there are no patches.",
    "S2 (fixes P2): Add a test-suite input to diff-input. Change 'given raw-diff' to 'given raw-diff' plus 'given test-manifest' that describes the test suite. Pass test-manifest to run-tests.",
    "S3 (fixes P3): Replace 'report is structured with summary, findings, and verdict' with 'contains(review-report, \"Summary\") and contains(review-report, \"Findings\") and contains(review-report, \"Verdict\")' — a pure ⊢= structural check.",
    "S4 (improvement): Add a conditional oracle on compile-report: '⊨ if has-vulnerabilities = false then verdict = \"clean\"'. This makes the zero-vulnerability case explicit."
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ length(problems) ≥ 1 → ✓ (4 problems)
--   ⊨ each problem has a corresponding suggestion → ✓ (S1→P1+P4, S2→P2, S3→P3, S4→new)
--   ⊨ suggestions are actionable Cell syntax changes → ✓ (all specify concrete given?/⊢= rewrites)

-- state after frame 6: critique frozen.
-- Ready set: { redesign } — critique→problems available via given?

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 7: evaluate redesign (soft cell, LLM) — iteration 1
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { redesign }
-- critique→problems is not ⊥ (critique was not skipped — guard passed)
-- given? tolerates ⊥ but receives actual values here.

⊢ redesign
  given §program ≡ §«...»
  given? critique→problems ≡ ["P1...", "P2...", "P3...", "P4..."]
  given? critique→suggestions ≡ ["S1...", "S2...", "S3...", "S4..."]
  yield §program'

  ∴ Apply suggestions to fix the problems in the program...

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Applying S1 (given? for zero-vuln path), S2 (test-manifest input),
-- S3 (structural oracle), S4 (conditional clean verdict):

  yield §program' ≡ §«
    ⊢ diff-input
      given raw-diff
      given test-manifest
      yield raw-diff, test-manifest
      ⊨ raw-diff is a valid unified diff format
      ⊨ test-manifest lists test names and expected outcomes

    ⊢ parse-diff ▸ crystallized
      given diff-input→raw-diff
      yield file-list[], change-regions[]
      ⊢= parse unified diff into structured file list and change regions
      ⊨ length(file-list) ≥ 1
      ⊨ each change-region maps to a file in file-list

    ⊢ classify-changes
      given parse-diff→change-regions
      yield risk-regions[]
      ∴ Classify each change region in «parse-diff→change-regions» by risk:
        high (auth, crypto, input handling), medium (data flow, API boundaries),
        low (UI, logging, comments). Tag each region with its risk level.
      ⊨ each region has a risk level ∈ { "high", "medium", "low" }
      ⊨ risk-regions covers all change-regions

    ⊢⊢ spawn-scanners
      given classify-changes→risk-regions where any(risk-regions, r -> r→risk != "low")
      given §vuln-scan-template
      yield §scan-cells[]
      until length(scan-cells) = count(classify-changes→risk-regions, r -> r→risk != "low")
      max 20
      accumulate
      ∴ For each high or medium risk region, spawn a vulnerability scanner cell.
      ⊨ each scan-cell targets exactly one risk region

    ⊢ vuln-scan-template
      given region
      given risk-level
      yield findings[], severity
      ∴ Scan «region» for vulnerability patterns appropriate to its «risk-level»:
        - high: SQL injection, XSS, CSRF, buffer overflow, insecure deserialization,
          hardcoded secrets, authentication bypass
        - medium: data leakage, insecure defaults, missing rate limiting,
          unvalidated redirects
        Report each finding with type, location, severity, and evidence.
      ⊨ each finding has type, location, severity, and evidence
      ⊨ severity ∈ { "critical", "high", "medium", "low", "info" }

    ⊢ collect-findings
      given vuln-scan-*→findings
      given vuln-scan-*→severity
      yield all-findings[], has-vulnerabilities
      ⊢= all-findings ← flatten(vuln-scan-*→findings)
      ⊢= has-vulnerabilities ← len(all-findings) > 0

    ⊢ suggest-fixes
      given collect-findings→all-findings where collect-findings→has-vulnerabilities = true
      given parse-diff→file-list
      yield patches[], explanations[]
      ∴ For each vulnerability in «collect-findings→all-findings», generate a
        concrete code fix with explanation.
      ⊨ length(patches) = length(collect-findings→all-findings)
      ⊨ each patch is syntactically valid code
      ⊨ each explanation describes the vulnerability and the fix

    ⊢ run-tests
      given? suggest-fixes→patches
      given diff-input→test-manifest
      given parse-diff→file-list
      yield test-results[], all-pass
      ∴ If «suggest-fixes→patches» is ⊥ (no vulnerabilities found, no patches),
        run the test suite against the original code to confirm it passes.
        Otherwise, apply «suggest-fixes→patches» to «parse-diff→file-list» and
        run «diff-input→test-manifest» tests. Report pass/fail per test.
      ⊨ test-results covers every test in test-manifest
      ⊢= all-pass ← all(test-results, t -> t→status = "pass")

    ⊢ compile-report
      given collect-findings→all-findings
      given collect-findings→has-vulnerabilities
      given? suggest-fixes→patches
      given? suggest-fixes→explanations
      given run-tests→test-results
      given run-tests→all-pass
      yield review-report
      ∴ Compile a final security review report:
        - If «collect-findings→has-vulnerabilities» is false: report "No
          vulnerabilities found" with clean verdict.
        - Otherwise: summary of findings by severity, each finding with fix
          and test impact, overall verdict based on all-pass.
      ⊨ contains(review-report, "Summary") and contains(review-report, "Findings") and contains(review-report, "Verdict")
      ⊨ if has-vulnerabilities = false then contains(review-report, "clean")
      ⊨ if all-pass = true and has-vulnerabilities = true then contains(review-report, "safe to merge")
      ⊨ if all-pass = false then contains(review-report, "regressions")
  »

